explanation: The target function itself does not call any <string.h> routines, so any potential MISRA C string/buffer violations must come from functions it invokes or from control/data values that determine which callees run. Include: 1) All direct callees (OS_Posix_TableMutex_Init, OS_Posix_TaskAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_QueueAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_BinSemAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_CountSemAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_MutexAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_ModuleAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_TimeBaseAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_StreamAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_DirAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_FileSysAPI_Impl_Init, OS_Posix_CondVarAPI_Impl_Init) — each may internally use memcpy/strcpy/etc.; their implementations must be inspected to determine any out‑of‑bounds accesses. 2) OS_Posix_GetSchedulerParams — called by OS_Posix_TaskAPI_Impl_Init (present in the static call graph), so its code must be examined for string functions. 3) Control and type symbols (OS_SUCCESS, osal_objtype_t, int32, and all OS_OBJECT_TYPE_* enum constants used in the switch) — these determine which initialization path(s) execute and whether the initial TableMutex init short‑circuits; they are needed to reason about reachable callees and correct argument/size semantics when following data flow into the callees. Together these symbols give the call targets and control/context needed to assess any use of <string.h> functions for potential out‑of‑bounds accesses.
